4/** \file
5 *
6 * Generator is a class used to encapsulate the building of Funcs in user
7 * pipelines. A Generator is agnostic to JIT vs AOT compilation; it can be used for
8 * either purpose, but is especially convenient to use for AOT compilation.
9 *
10 * A Generator explicitly declares the Inputs and Outputs associated for a given
11 * pipeline, and (optionally) separates the code for constructing the outputs from the code from
12 * scheduling them. For instance:
13 *
14 * \code
15 * class Blur : public Generator<Blur> {
16 * public:
17 * Input<Func> input{"input", UInt(16), 2};
18 * Output<Func> output{"output", UInt(16), 2};
19 * void generate() {
20 * blur_x(x, y) = (input(x, y) + input(x+1, y) + input(x+2, y))/3;
21 * blur_y(x, y) = (blur_x(x, y) + blur_x(x, y+1) + blur_x(x, y+2))/3;
22 * output(x, y) = blur(x, y);
23 * }
24 * void schedule() {
25 * blur_y.split(y, y, yi, 8).parallel(y).vectorize(x, 8);
26 * blur_x.store_at(blur_y, y).compute_at(blur_y, yi).vectorize(x, 8);
27 * }
28 * private:
29 * Var x, y, xi, yi;
30 * Func blur_x, blur_y;
31 * };
32 * \endcode
33 *
34 * Halide can compile a Generator into the correct pipeline by introspecting these
35 * values and constructing an appropriate signature based on them.
36 *
37 * A Generator provides implementations of two methods:
38 *
39 * - generate(), which must fill in all Output Func(s); it may optionally also do scheduling
40 * if no schedule() method is present.
41 * - schedule(), which (if present) should contain all scheduling code.
42 *
43 * Inputs can be any C++ scalar type:
44 *
45 * \code
46 * Input<float> radius{"radius"};
47 * Input<int32_t> increment{"increment"};
48 * \endcode
49 *
50 * An Input<Func> is (essentially) like an ImageParam, except that it may (or may
51 * not) not be backed by an actual buffer, and thus has no defined extents.
52 *
53 * \code
54 * Input<Func> input{"input", Float(32), 2};
55 * \endcode
56 *
57 * You can optionally make the type and/or dimensions of Input<Func> unspecified,
58 * in which case the value is simply inferred from the actual Funcs passed to them.
59 * Of course, if you specify an explicit Type or Dimension, we still require the
60 * input Func to match, or a compilation error results.
61 *
62 * \code
63 * Input<Func> input{ "input", 3 }; // require 3-dimensional Func,
64 * // but leave Type unspecified
65 * \endcode
66 *
67 * A Generator must explicitly list the output(s) it produces:
68 *
69 * \code
70 * Output<Func> output{"output", Float(32), 2};
71 * \endcode
72 *
73 * You can specify an output that returns a Tuple by specifying a list of Types:
74 *
75 * \code
76 * class Tupler : Generator<Tupler> {
77 * Input<Func> input{"input", Int(32), 2};
78 * Output<Func> output{"output", {Float(32), UInt(8)}, 2};
79 * void generate() {
80 * Var x, y;
81 * Expr a = cast<float>(input(x, y));
82 * Expr b = cast<uint8_t>(input(x, y));
83 * output(x, y) = Tuple(a, b);
84 * }
85 * };
86 * \endcode
87 *
88 * You can also specify Output<X> for any scalar type (except for Handle types);
89 * this is merely syntactic sugar on top of a zero-dimensional Func, but can be
90 * quite handy, especially when used with multiple outputs:
91 *
92 * \code
93 * Output<float> sum{"sum"}; // equivalent to Output<Func> {"sum", Float(32), 0}
94 * \endcode
95 *
96 * As with Input<Func>, you can optionally make the type and/or dimensions of an
97 * Output<Func> unspecified; any unspecified types must be resolved via an
98 * implicit GeneratorParam in order to use top-level compilation.
99 *
100 * You can also declare an *array* of Input or Output, by using an array type
101 * as the type parameter:
102 *
103 * \code
104 * // Takes exactly 3 images and outputs exactly 3 sums.
105 * class SumRowsAndColumns : Generator<SumRowsAndColumns> {
106 * Input<Func[3]> inputs{"inputs", Float(32), 2};
107 * Input<int32_t[2]> extents{"extents"};
108 * Output<Func[3]> sums{"sums", Float(32), 1};
109 * void generate() {
110 * assert(inputs.size() == sums.size());
111 * // assume all inputs are same extent
112 * Expr width = extent[0];
113 * Expr height = extent[1];
114 * for (size_t i = 0; i < inputs.size(); ++i) {
115 * RDom r(0, width, 0, height);
116 * sums[i]() = 0.f;
117 * sums[i]() += inputs[i](r.x, r.y);
118 * }
119 * }
120 * };
121 * \endcode
122 *
123 * You can also leave array size unspecified, with some caveats:
124 * - For ahead-of-time compilation, Inputs must have a concrete size specified
125 * via a GeneratorParam at build time (e.g., pyramid.size=3)
126 * - For JIT compilation via a Stub, Inputs array sizes will be inferred
127 * from the vector passed.
128 * - For ahead-of-time compilation, Outputs may specify a concrete size
129 * via a GeneratorParam at build time (e.g., pyramid.size=3), or the
130 * size can be specified via a resize() method.
131 *
132 * \code
133 * class Pyramid : public Generator<Pyramid> {
134 * public:
135 * GeneratorParam<int32_t> levels{"levels", 10};
136 * Input<Func> input{ "input", Float(32), 2 };
137 * Output<Func[]> pyramid{ "pyramid", Float(32), 2 };
138 * void generate() {
139 * pyramid.resize(levels);
140 * pyramid[0](x, y) = input(x, y);
141 * for (int i = 1; i < pyramid.size(); i++) {
142 * pyramid[i](x, y) = (pyramid[i-1](2*x, 2*y) +
143 * pyramid[i-1](2*x+1, 2*y) +
144 * pyramid[i-1](2*x, 2*y+1) +
145 * pyramid[i-1](2*x+1, 2*y+1))/4;
146 * }
147 * }
148 * };
149 * \endcode
150 *
151 * A Generator can also be customized via compile-time parameters (GeneratorParams),
152 * which affect code generation.
153 *
154 * GeneratorParams, Inputs, and Outputs are (by convention) always
155 * public and always declared at the top of the Generator class, in the order
156 *
157 * \code
158 * GeneratorParam(s)
159 * Input<Func>(s)
160 * Input<non-Func>(s)
161 * Output<Func>(s)
162 * \endcode
163 *
164 * Note that the Inputs and Outputs will appear in the C function call in the order
165 * they are declared. All Input<Func> and Output<Func> are represented as halide_buffer_t;
166 * all other Input<> are the appropriate C++ scalar type. (GeneratorParams are
167 * always referenced by name, not position, so their order is irrelevant.)
168 *
169 * All Inputs and Outputs must have explicit names, and all such names must match
170 * the regex [A-Za-z][A-Za-z_0-9]* (i.e., essentially a C/C++ variable name, with
171 * some extra restrictions on underscore use). By convention, the name should match
172 * the member-variable name.
173 *
174 * You can dynamically add Inputs and Outputs to your Generator via adding a
175 * configure() method; if present, it will be called before generate(). It can
176 * examine GeneratorParams but it may not examine predeclared Inputs or Outputs;
177 * the only thing it should do is call add_input<>() and/or add_output<>(), or call
178 * set_type()/set_dimensions()/set_array_size() on an Input or Output with an unspecified type.
179 * Added inputs will be appended (in order) after predeclared Inputs but before
180 * any Outputs; added outputs will be appended after predeclared Outputs.
181 *
182 * Note that the pointers returned by add_input() and add_output() are owned
183 * by the Generator and will remain valid for the Generator's lifetime; user code
184 * should not attempt to delete or free them.
185 *
186 * \code
187 * class MultiSum : public Generator<MultiSum> {
188 * public:
189 * GeneratorParam<int32_t> input_count{"input_count", 10};
190 * Output<Func> output{ "output", Float(32), 2 };
191 *
192 * void configure() {
193 * for (int i = 0; i < input_count; ++i) {
194 * extra_inputs.push_back(
195 * add_input<Func>("input_" + std::to_string(i), Float(32), 2);
196 * }
197 * }
198 *
199 * void generate() {
200 * Expr sum = 0.f;
201 * for (int i = 0; i < input_count; ++i) {
202 * sum += (*extra_inputs)[i](x, y);
203 * }
204 * output(x, y) = sum;
205 * }
206 * private:
207 * std::vector<Input<Func>* extra_inputs;
208 * };
209 * \endcode
210 *
211 * All Generators have two GeneratorParams that are implicitly provided
212 * by the base class:
213 *
214 * GeneratorParam<Target> target{"target", Target()};
215 * GeneratorParam<AutoschedulerParams> autoscheduler{"autoscheduler", {}}
216 *
217 * - 'target' is the Halide::Target for which the Generator is producing code.
218 * It is read-only during the Generator's lifetime, and must not be modified;
219 * its value should always be filled in by the calling code: either the Halide
220 * build system (for ahead-of-time compilation), or ordinary C++ code
221 * (for JIT compilation).
222 * - 'autoscheduler' is a string-to-string map that is used to indicates whether
223 * and how an auto-scheduler should be run for this Generator:
224 * - if empty, the Generator should schedule its Funcs as it sees fit; no autoscheduler will be run.
225 * - if the 'name' key is set, it should be one of the known autoschedulers
226 * provided with this release of Halide, which will be used to schedule
227 * the Funcs in the Generator. In this case, the Generator should only
228 * provide estimate()s for its Funcs, and not call any other scheduling methods.
229 * - Other keys may be specified in the params, on a per-autoscheduler
230 * basis, to optimize or enhance the automatically-generated schedule.
231 * See documentation for each autoscheduler for options.
232 *
233 * Generators are added to a global registry to simplify AOT build mechanics; this
234 * is done by simply using the HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR macro at global scope:
235 *
236 * \code
237 * HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR(ExampleGen, jit_example)
238 * \endcode
239 *
240 * The registered name of the Generator is provided must match the same rules as
241 * Input names, above.
242 *
243 * Note that the class name of the generated Stub class will match the registered
244 * name by default; if you want to vary it (typically, to include namespaces),
245 * you can add it as an optional third argument:
246 *
247 * \code
248 * HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR(ExampleGen, jit_example, SomeNamespace::JitExampleStub)
249 * \endcode
250 *
251 * Note that a Generator is always executed with a specific Target assigned to it,
252 * that you can access via the get_target() method. (You should *not* use the
253 * global get_target_from_environment(), etc. methods provided in Target.h)
254 *
255 * (Note that there are older variations of Generator that differ from what's
256 * documented above; these are still supported but not described here. See
257 * https://github.com/halide/Halide/wiki/Old-Generator-Documentation for
258 * more information.)
259 */

300template<typename T>
301HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE std::string enum_to_string(const std::map<std::string, T> &enum_map, const T &t) {
302 for (const auto &key_value : enum_map) {
303 if (t == key_value.second) {
304 return key_value.first;
305 }
306 }
307 user_error << "Enumeration value not found.\n";
308 return "";
309}
310
311template<typename T>
312T enum_from_string(const std::map<std::string, T> &enum_map, const std::string &s) {
313 auto it = enum_map.find(s);
314 user_assert(it != enum_map.end()) << "Enumeration value not found: " << s << "\n";
315 return it->second;
316}

369// select_type<> is to std::conditional as switch is to if:
370// it allows a multiway compile-time type definition via the form
371//
372// select_type<cond<condition1, type1>,
373// cond<condition2, type2>,
374// ....
375// cond<conditionN, typeN>>::type
376//
377// Note that the conditions are evaluated in order; the first evaluating to true
378// is chosen.
379//
380// Note that if no conditions evaluate to true, the resulting type is illegal
381// and will produce a compilation error. (You can provide a default by simply
382// using cond<true, SomeType> as the final entry.)
383template<bool B, typename T>
384struct cond {
385 static constexpr bool value = B;
386 using type = T;
387};
388
389template<typename First, typename... Rest>
390struct select_type : std::conditional<First::value, typename First::type, typename select_type<Rest...>::type> {};
391
392template<typename First>
393struct select_type<First> { using type = typename std::conditional<First::value, typename First::type, void>::type; };

494// This is strictly some syntactic sugar to suppress certain compiler warnings.
495template<typename FROM, typename TO>
496struct Convert {
497 template<typename TO2 = TO, typename std::enable_if<!std::is_same<TO2, bool>::value>::type * = nullptr>
498 inline static TO2 value(const FROM &from) {
499 return static_cast<TO2>(from);
500 }
501
502 template<typename TO2 = TO, typename std::enable_if<std::is_same<TO2, bool>::value>::type * = nullptr>
503 inline static TO2 value(const FROM &from) {
504 return from != 0;
505 }
506};

508template<typename T>
509class GeneratorParamImpl : public GeneratorParamBase {
510public:
511 using type = T;
512
513 GeneratorParamImpl(const std::string &name, const T &value)
514 : GeneratorParamBase(name), value_(value) {
515 }
516
517 T value() const {
518 this->check_value_readable();
519 return value_;
520 }
521
522 operator T() const {
523 return this->value();
524 }
525
526 operator Expr() const {
527 return make_const(type_of<T>(), this->value());
528 }

530#define HALIDE_GENERATOR_PARAM_TYPED_SETTER(TYPE) \
531 void set(const TYPE &new_value) override { \
532 typed_setter_impl<TYPE>(new_value, #TYPE); \
533 }

558 void set(const std::string &new_value) {

561 }

563protected:
564 virtual void set_impl(const T &new_value) {
565 check_value_writable();
566 value_ = new_value;
567 }
568
569 // Needs to be protected to allow GeneratorParam<LoopLevel>::set() override
570 T value_;
571
572private:
573 // If FROM->T is not legal, fail
574 template<typename FROM, typename std::enable_if<
575 !std::is_convertible<FROM, T>::value>::type * = nullptr>
576 HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE void typed_setter_impl(const FROM &, const char *msg) {
577 fail_wrong_type(msg);
578 }
579
580 // If FROM and T are identical, just assign
581 template<typename FROM, typename std::enable_if<
582 std::is_same<FROM, T>::value>::type * = nullptr>
583 HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE void typed_setter_impl(const FROM &value, const char *msg) {
584 check_value_writable();
585 value_ = value;
586 }
587
588 // If both FROM->T and T->FROM are legal, ensure it's lossless
589 template<typename FROM, typename std::enable_if<
590 !std::is_same<FROM, T>::value &&
591 std::is_convertible<FROM, T>::value &&
592 std::is_convertible<T, FROM>::value>::type * = nullptr>
593 HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE void typed_setter_impl(const FROM &value, const char *msg) {
594 check_value_writable();
595 const T t = Convert<FROM, T>::value(value);
596 const FROM value2 = Convert<T, FROM>::value(t);
597 if (value2 != value) {
598 fail_wrong_type(msg);
599 }
600 value_ = t;
601 }
602
603 // If FROM->T is legal but T->FROM is not, just assign
604 template<typename FROM, typename std::enable_if<
605 !std::is_same<FROM, T>::value &&
606 std::is_convertible<FROM, T>::value &&
607 !std::is_convertible<T, FROM>::value>::type * = nullptr>
608 HALIDE_ALWAYS_INLINE void typed_setter_impl(const FROM &value, const char *msg) {
609 check_value_writable();
610 value_ = value;
611 }
612};

614// Stubs for type-specific implementations of GeneratorParam, to avoid
615// many complex enable_if<> statements that were formerly spread through the
616// implementation. Note that not all of these need to be templated classes,
617// (e.g. for GeneratorParam_Target, T == Target always), but are declared
618// that way for symmetry of declaration.
619template<typename T>
620class GeneratorParam_Target : public GeneratorParamImpl<T> {
621public:
622 GeneratorParam_Target(const std::string &name, const T &value)
623 : GeneratorParamImpl<T>(name, value) {
624 }
625
626 void set_from_string(const std::string &new_value_string) override {
627 this->set(Target(new_value_string));

688class GeneratorParam_LoopLevel : public GeneratorParamImpl<LoopLevel> {
689public:
690 GeneratorParam_LoopLevel(const std::string &name, const LoopLevel &value)
691 : GeneratorParamImpl<LoopLevel>(name, value) {
692 }
693
694 using GeneratorParamImpl<LoopLevel>::set;
695
696 void set(const LoopLevel &value) override {
697 // Don't call check_value_writable(): It's OK to set a LoopLevel after generate().
698 // check_value_writable();
699
700 // This looks odd, but is deliberate:
701
702 // First, mutate the existing contents to match the value passed in,
703 // so that any existing usage of the LoopLevel now uses the newer value.
704 // (Strictly speaking, this is really only necessary if this method
705 // is called after generate(): before generate(), there is no usage
706 // to be concerned with.)
707 value_.set(value);
708
709 // Then, reset the value itself so that it points to the same LoopLevelContents
710 // as the value passed in. (Strictly speaking, this is really only
711 // useful if this method is called before generate(): afterwards, it's
712 // too late to alter the code to refer to a different LoopLevelContents.)
713 value_ = value;
714 }
715
716 void set_from_string(const std::string &new_value_string) override {
717 if (new_value_string == "root") {
718 this->set(LoopLevel::root());
719 } else if (new_value_string == "inlined") {
720 this->set(LoopLevel::inlined());
721 } else {
722 user_error << "Unable to parse " << this->name() << ": " << new_value_string;
723 }
724 }
725
726 std::string get_default_value() const override {
727 // This is dodgy but safe in this case: we want to
728 // see what the value of our LoopLevel is *right now*,
729 // so we make a copy and lock the copy so we can inspect it.
730 // (Note that ordinarily this is a bad idea, since LoopLevels
731 // can be mutated later on; however, this method is only
732 // called by the Generator infrastructure, on LoopLevels that
733 // will never be mutated, so this is really just an elaborate way
734 // to avoid runtime assertions.)
735 LoopLevel copy;
736 copy.set(this->value());
737 copy.lock();
738 if (copy.is_inlined()) {
739 return "LoopLevel::inlined()";
740 } else if (copy.is_root()) {
741 return "LoopLevel::root()";
742 } else {
743 internal_error;
744 return "";
745 }
746 }
747
748 std::string call_to_string(const std::string &v) const override {
749 internal_error;
750 return std::string();
751 }
752
753 std::string get_c_type() const override {
754 return "LoopLevel";
755 }
756
757 bool is_looplevel_param() const override {
758 return true;
759 }
760};

762template<typename T>
763class GeneratorParam_Arithmetic : public GeneratorParamImpl<T> {
764public:
765 GeneratorParam_Arithmetic(const std::string &name,
766 const T &value,
767 const T &min = std::numeric_limits<T>::lowest(),
768 const T &max = std::numeric_limits<T>::max())
769 : GeneratorParamImpl<T>(name, value), min(min), max(max) {
770 // call set() to ensure value is clamped to min/max
771 this->set(value);
772 }
773
774 void set_impl(const T &new_value) override {
775 user_assert(new_value >= min && new_value <= max) << "Value out of range: " << new_value;
776 GeneratorParamImpl<T>::set_impl(new_value);
777 }
778
779 void set_from_string(const std::string &new_value_string) override {
780 std::istringstream iss(new_value_string);
781 T t;
782 // All one-byte ints int8 and uint8 should be parsed as integers, not chars --
783 // including 'char' itself. (Note that sizeof(bool) is often-but-not-always-1,
784 // so be sure to exclude that case.)
785 if (sizeof(T) == sizeof(char) && !std::is_same<T, bool>::value) {
786 int i;
787 iss >> i;
788 t = (T)i;
789 } else {
790 iss >> t;
791 }
792 user_assert(!iss.fail() && iss.get() == EOF) << "Unable to parse: " << new_value_string;
793 this->set(t);
794 }
795
796 std::string get_default_value() const override {
797 std::ostringstream oss;
798 oss << this->value();
799 if (std::is_same<T, float>::value) {
800 // If the constant has no decimal point ("1")
801 // we must append one before appending "f"
802 if (oss.str().find('.') == std::string::npos) {
803 oss << ".";
804 }
805 oss << "f";
806 }
807 return oss.str();
808 }
809
810 std::string call_to_string(const std::string &v) const override {
811 std::ostringstream oss;
812 oss << "std::to_string(" << v << ")";
813 return oss.str();
814 }
815
816 std::string get_c_type() const override {
817 std::ostringstream oss;
818 if (std::is_same<T, float>::value) {
819 return "float";
820 } else if (std::is_same<T, double>::value) {
821 return "double";
822 } else if (std::is_integral<T>::value) {
823 if (std::is_unsigned<T>::value) {
824 oss << "u";
825 }
826 oss << "int" << (sizeof(T) * 8) << "_t";
827 return oss.str();
828 } else {
829 user_error << "Unknown arithmetic type\n";
830 return "";
831 }
832 }
833
834private:
835 const T min, max;
836};

838template<typename T>
839class GeneratorParam_Bool : public GeneratorParam_Arithmetic<T> {
840public:
841 GeneratorParam_Bool(const std::string &name, const T &value)
842 : GeneratorParam_Arithmetic<T>(name, value) {
843 }
844
845 void set_from_string(const std::string &new_value_string) override {
846 bool v = false;
847 if (new_value_string == "true" || new_value_string == "True") {
848 v = true;
849 } else if (new_value_string == "false" || new_value_string == "False") {

853 }
854 this->set(v);
855 }
856

858 return this->value() ? "true" : "false";
859 }
860
861 std::string call_to_string(const std::string &v) const override {
862 std::ostringstream oss;
863 oss << "std::string((" << v << ") ? \"true\" : \"false\")";
864 return oss.str();
865 }
866

868 return "bool";
869 }
870};

872template<typename T>
873class GeneratorParam_Enum : public GeneratorParamImpl<T> {
874public:
875 GeneratorParam_Enum(const std::string &name, const T &value, const std::map<std::string, T> &enum_map)
876 : GeneratorParamImpl<T>(name, value), enum_map(enum_map) {
877 }
878
879 // define a "set" that takes our specific enum (but don't hide the inherited virtual functions)
880 using GeneratorParamImpl<T>::set;
881
882 template<typename T2 = T, typename std::enable_if<!std::is_same<T2, Type>::value>::type * = nullptr>
883 void set(const T &e) {
884 this->set_impl(e);
885 }
886
887 void set_from_string(const std::string &new_value_string) override {
888 auto it = enum_map.find(new_value_string);
889 user_assert(it != enum_map.end()) << "Enumeration value not found: " << new_value_string;
890 this->set_impl(it->second);
891 }
892
893 std::string call_to_string(const std::string &v) const override {
894 return "Enum_" + this->name() + "_map().at(" + v + ")";
895 }
896
897 std::string get_c_type() const override {
898 return "Enum_" + this->name();
899 }
900
901 std::string get_default_value() const override {
902 return "Enum_" + this->name() + "::" + enum_to_string(enum_map, this->value());
903 }
904
905 std::string get_type_decls() const override {
906 std::ostringstream oss;
907 oss << "enum class Enum_" << this->name() << " {\n";
908 for (auto key_value : enum_map) {
909 oss << " " << key_value.first << ",\n";
910 }
911 oss << "};\n";
912 oss << "\n";
913
914 // TODO: since we generate the enums, we could probably just use a vector (or array!) rather than a map,
915 // since we can ensure that the enum values are a nice tight range.
916 oss << "inline HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE const std::map<Enum_" << this->name() << ", std::string>& Enum_" << this->name() << "_map() {\n";
917 oss << " static const std::map<Enum_" << this->name() << ", std::string> m = {\n";
918 for (auto key_value : enum_map) {
919 oss << " { Enum_" << this->name() << "::" << key_value.first << ", \"" << key_value.first << "\"},\n";
920 }
921 oss << " };\n";
922 oss << " return m;\n";
923 oss << "};\n";
924 return oss.str();
925 }
926
927private:
928 const std::map<std::string, T> enum_map;
929};

978template<typename T>
979using GeneratorParamImplBase =
980 typename select_type<
981 cond<std::is_same<T, Target>::value, GeneratorParam_Target<T>>,
982#ifdef HALIDE_ALLOW_LEGACY_AUTOSCHEDULER_API
983 cond<std::is_same<T, MachineParams>::value, GeneratorParam_MachineParams<T>>,
984#endif
985 cond<std::is_same<T, LoopLevel>::value, GeneratorParam_LoopLevel>,
986 cond<std::is_same<T, std::string>::value, GeneratorParam_String<T>>,
987 cond<std::is_same<T, Type>::value, GeneratorParam_Type<T>>,
988 cond<std::is_same<T, bool>::value, GeneratorParam_Bool<T>>,
989 cond<std::is_arithmetic<T>::value, GeneratorParam_Arithmetic<T>>,
990 cond<std::is_enum<T>::value, GeneratorParam_Enum<T>>>::type;

994/** GeneratorParam is a templated class that can be used to modify the behavior
995 * of the Generator at code-generation time. GeneratorParams are commonly
996 * specified in build files (e.g. Makefile) to customize the behavior of
997 * a given Generator, thus they have a very constrained set of types to allow
998 * for efficient specification via command-line flags. A GeneratorParam can be:
999 * - any float or int type.
1000 * - bool
1001 * - enum
1002 * - Halide::Target
1003 * - Halide::Type
1004 * - std::string
1005 * Please don't use std::string unless there's no way to do what you want with some
1006 * other type; in particular, don't use this if you can use enum instead.
1007 * All GeneratorParams have a default value. Arithmetic types can also
1008 * optionally specify min and max. Enum types must specify a string-to-value
1009 * map.
1010 *
1011 * Halide::Type is treated as though it were an enum, with the mappings:
1012 *
1013 * "int8" Halide::Int(8)
1014 * "int16" Halide::Int(16)
1015 * "int32" Halide::Int(32)
1016 * "uint8" Halide::UInt(8)
1017 * "uint16" Halide::UInt(16)
1018 * "uint32" Halide::UInt(32)
1019 * "float32" Halide::Float(32)
1020 * "float64" Halide::Float(64)
1021 *
1022 * No vector Types are currently supported by this mapping.
1023 *
1024 */
1025template<typename T>
1026class GeneratorParam : public Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T> {
1027public:
1028 template<typename T2 = T, typename std::enable_if<!std::is_same<T2, std::string>::value>::type * = nullptr>
1029 GeneratorParam(const std::string &name, const T &value)
1030 : Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T>(name, value) {
1031 }
1032
1033 GeneratorParam(const std::string &name, const T &value, const T &min, const T &max)
1034 : Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T>(name, value, min, max) {
1035 }
1036
1037 GeneratorParam(const std::string &name, const T &value, const std::map<std::string, T> &enum_map)
1038 : Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T>(name, value, enum_map) {
1039 }
1040
1041 GeneratorParam(const std::string &name, const std::string &value)
1042 : Internal::GeneratorParamImplBase<T>(name, value) {
1043 }
1044};

1223/* min and max are tricky as the language support for these is in the std
1224 * namespace. In order to make this work, forwarding functions are used that
1225 * are declared in a namespace that has std::min and std::max in scope.
1226 */
1227namespace Internal {
1228namespace GeneratorMinMax {
1229
1230using std::max;
1231using std::min;
1232
1233template<typename Other, typename T>
1234auto min_forward(const Other &a, const GeneratorParam<T> &b) -> decltype(min(a, (T)b)) {
1235 return min(a, (T)b);
1236}
1237template<typename Other, typename T>
1238auto min_forward(const GeneratorParam<T> &a, const Other &b) -> decltype(min((T)a, b)) {
1239 return min((T)a, b);
1240}
1241
1242template<typename Other, typename T>
1243auto max_forward(const Other &a, const GeneratorParam<T> &b) -> decltype(max(a, (T)b)) {
1244 return max(a, (T)b);
1245}
1246template<typename Other, typename T>
1247auto max_forward(const GeneratorParam<T> &a, const Other &b) -> decltype(max((T)a, b)) {
1248 return max((T)a, b);
1249}
1250
1251} // namespace GeneratorMinMax
1252} // namespace Internal

1255 * Will automatically import std::min. Returns type of underlying min call. */
1256// @{

1259 return Internal::GeneratorMinMax::min_forward(a, b);

1261template<typename Other, typename T>

1291/**
1292 * StubInputBuffer is the placeholder that a Stub uses when it requires
1293 * a Buffer for an input (rather than merely a Func or Expr). It is constructed
1294 * to allow only two possible sorts of input:
1295 * -- Assignment of an Input<Buffer<>>, with compatible type and dimensions,
1296 * essentially allowing us to pipe a parameter from an enclosing Generator to an internal Stub.
1297 * -- Assignment of a Buffer<>, with compatible type and dimensions,
1298 * causing the Input<Buffer<>> to become a precompiled buffer in the generated code.
1299 */
1300template<typename T = void, int Dims = Buffer<>::AnyDims>
1301class StubInputBuffer {
1302 friend class StubInput;
1303 template<typename T2>
1304 friend class GeneratorInput_Buffer;
1305 template<typename T2, int D2>
1306 friend class StubInputBuffer;
1307
1308 Parameter parameter_;
1309
1310 HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE explicit StubInputBuffer(const Parameter &p)
1311 : parameter_(p) {
1312 // Create an empty 1-element buffer with the right runtime typing and dimensions,
1313 // which we'll use only to pass to can_convert_from() to verify this
1314 // Parameter is compatible with our constraints.
1315 Buffer<> other(p.type(), nullptr, std::vector<int>(p.dimensions(), 1));
1316 internal_assert((Buffer<T, Dims>::can_convert_from(other)));
1317 }
1318
1319 template<typename T2, int D2>
1320 HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE static Parameter parameter_from_buffer(const Buffer<T2, D2> &b) {
1321 internal_assert(b.defined());
1322 user_assert((Buffer<T, Dims>::can_convert_from(b)));
1323 Parameter p(b.type(), true, b.dimensions());
1324 p.set_buffer(b);
1325 return p;
1326 }
1327
1328public:
1329 StubInputBuffer() = default;
1330
1331 // *not* explicit -- this ctor should only be used when you want
1332 // to pass a literal Buffer<> for a Stub Input; this Buffer<> will be
1333 // compiled into the Generator's product, rather than becoming
1334 // a runtime Parameter.
1335 template<typename T2, int D2>
1336 StubInputBuffer(const Buffer<T2, D2> &b)
1337 : parameter_(parameter_from_buffer(b)) {
1338 }
1339
1340 template<typename T2>
1341 static std::vector<Parameter> to_parameter_vector(const StubInputBuffer<T2> &t) {
1342 return {t.parameter_};
1343 }
1344
1345 template<typename T2>
1346 static std::vector<Parameter> to_parameter_vector(const std::vector<StubInputBuffer<T2>> &v) {
1347 std::vector<Parameter> r;
1348 r.reserve(v.size());
1349 for (const auto &s : v) {
1350 r.push_back(s.parameter_);
1351 }
1352 return r;
1353 }
1354};

1462/** GIOBase is the base class for all GeneratorInput<> and GeneratorOutput<>
1463 * instantiations; it is not part of the public API and should never be
1464 * used directly by user code.
1465 *
1466 * Every GIOBase instance can be either a single value or an array-of-values;
1467 * each of these values can be an Expr or a Func. (Note that for an
1468 * array-of-values, the types/dimensions of all values in the array must match.)
1469 *
1470 * A GIOBase can have multiple Types, in which case it represents a Tuple.
1471 * (Note that Tuples are currently only supported for GeneratorOutput, but
1472 * it is likely that GeneratorInput will be extended to support Tuple as well.)
1473 *
1474 * The array-size, type(s), and dimensions can all be left "unspecified" at
1475 * creation time, in which case they may assume values provided by a Stub.

1477 * values will assert-fail; you must ensure that all unspecified values are
1478 * filled in prior to use.)

1679// When forwarding methods to ImageParam, Func, etc., we must take
1680// care with the return types: many of the methods return a reference-to-self
1681// (e.g., ImageParam&); since we create temporaries for most of these forwards,
1682// returning a ref will crater because it refers to a now-defunct section of the
1683// stack. Happily, simply removing the reference is solves this, since all of the
1684// types in question satisfy the property of copies referring to the same underlying
1685// structure (returning references is just an optimization). Since this is verbose
1686// and used in several places, we'll use a helper macro:
1687#define HALIDE_FORWARD_METHOD(Class, Method) \
1688 template<typename... Args> \
1689 inline auto Method(Args &&...args)->typename std::remove_reference<decltype(std::declval<Class>().Method(std::forward<Args>(args)...))>::type { \
1690 return this->template as<Class>().Method(std::forward<Args>(args)...); \
1691 }
1692
1693#define HALIDE_FORWARD_METHOD_CONST(Class, Method) \
1694 template<typename... Args> \
1695 inline auto Method(Args &&...args) const-> \
1696 typename std::remove_reference<decltype(std::declval<Class>().Method(std::forward<Args>(args)...))>::type { \
1697 this->check_gio_access(); \
1698 return this->template as<Class>().Method(std::forward<Args>(args)...); \
1699 }
1700

2525 HALIDE_NO_USER_CODE_INLINE void assign_from_func(const Func &f) {
2526 this->check_value_writable();
2527
2528 internal_assert(f.defined());
2529
2530 if (this->gio_types_defined()) {
2531 const auto &my_types = this->gio_types();
2532 user_assert(my_types.size() == f.types().size())
2533 << "Cannot assign Func \"" << f.name()
2534 << "\" to Output \"" << this->name() << "\"\n"
2535 << "Output " << this->name()
2536 << " is declared to have " << my_types.size() << " tuple elements"
2537 << " but Func " << f.name()
2538 << " has " << f.types().size() << " tuple elements.\n";
2539 for (size_t i = 0; i < my_types.size(); i++) {
2540 user_assert(my_types[i] == f.types().at(i))
2541 << "Cannot assign Func \"" << f.name()
2542 << "\" to Output \"" << this->name() << "\"\n"
2543 << (my_types.size() > 1 ? "In tuple element " + std::to_string(i) + ", " : "")
2544 << "Output " << this->name()
2545 << " has declared type " << my_types[i]
2546 << " but Func " << f.name()
2547 << " has type " << f.types().at(i) << "\n";
2548 }
2549 }
2550 if (this->dims_defined()) {
2551 user_assert(f.dimensions() == this->dims())
2552 << "Cannot assign Func \"" << f.name()
2553 << "\" to Output \"" << this->name() << "\"\n"
2554 << "Output " << this->name()
2555 << " has declared dimensionality " << this->dims()
2556 << " but Func " << f.name()
2557 << " has dimensionality " << f.dimensions() << "\n";
2558 }
2559
2560 internal_assert(this->exprs_.empty() && this->funcs_.size() == 1);
2561 user_assert(!this->funcs_.at(0).defined());

3021/** GeneratorContext is a class that is used when using Generators (or Stubs) directly;
3022 * it is used to allow the outer context (typically, either a Generator or "top-level" code)
3023 * to specify certain information to the inner context to ensure that inner and outer
3024 * Generators are compiled in a compatible way.
3025 *
3026 * If you are using this at "top level" (e.g. with the JIT), you can construct a GeneratorContext
3027 * with a Target:
3028 * \code
3029 * auto my_stub = MyStub(
3030 * GeneratorContext(get_target_from_environment()),
3031 * // inputs
3032 * { ... },
3033 * // generator params
3034 * { ... }
3035 * );
3036 * \endcode
3037 *
3038 * Note that all Generators embed a GeneratorContext, so if you are using a Stub
3039 * from within a Generator, you can just pass 'context()' for the GeneratorContext:
3040 * \code
3041 * struct SomeGen : Generator<SomeGen> {
3042 * void generate() {
3043 * ...
3044 * auto my_stub = MyStub(
3045 * context(), // GeneratorContext
3046 * // inputs
3047 * { ... },
3048 * // generator params
3049 * { ... }
3050 * );
3051 * ...
3052 * }
3053 * };
3054 * \endcode
3055 */
3056class GeneratorContext {
3057public:
3058 friend class Internal::GeneratorBase;
3059
3060#ifdef HALIDE_ALLOW_GENERATOR_EXTERNAL_CODE
3061 using ExternsMap = std::map<std::string, ExternalCode>;
3062#endif
3063
3064#ifdef HALIDE_ALLOW_LEGACY_AUTOSCHEDULER_API
3065 explicit GeneratorContext(const Target &t,
3066 bool auto_schedule = false,
3067 const MachineParams &machine_params = MachineParams::generic());
3068#else
3069 explicit GeneratorContext(const Target &t);
3070 explicit GeneratorContext(const Target &t,
3071 const AutoschedulerParams &autoscheduler_params);
3072#endif
3073
3074 GeneratorContext() = default;
3075 GeneratorContext(const GeneratorContext &) = default;
3076 GeneratorContext &operator=(const GeneratorContext &) = default;
3077 GeneratorContext(GeneratorContext &&) = default;
3078 GeneratorContext &operator=(GeneratorContext &&) = default;

3465 // Note that it is explicitly legal to override init_from_context(), so that you can (say)
3466 // create a modified context with a different Target (eg with features enabled or disabled), but...
3467 //
3468 // *** WARNING ***
3469 //
3470 // Modifying the context here can be fraught with subtle hazards, especially when used
3471 // in conjunction with compiling to multitarget output. Adding or removing Feature
3472 // flags could break your build (if you are lucky), or cause subtle runtime failures (if unlucky)...
3473 //
3474 // e.g. in the latter case, say you decided to enable AVX512_SapphireRapids as an experiment,
3475 // and override init_from_context() to do just that. You'd end up being crashy on pre-AVX512
3476 // hardware, because the code that Halide injects to do runtime CPU feature detection at runtime
3477 // doesn't know it needs to do the runtime detection for this flag.
3478 //
3479 // Even if you are using multitarget output, using this as a 'hook' to enable or disable Features
3480 // can produce hard-to-maintain code in the long term: Halide has dozens of feature flags now,
3481 // many of which are orthogonal to each other and/or specific to a certain architecture
3482 // (or sub-architecture). The interaction between 'orthogonal' flags like this is essentially
3483 // Undefined Behavior (e.g. if I enable the SSE41 Feature on a Target where arch = RISCV, what happens?
3484 // Is it ignored? Does it fail to compile? Something else?). The point here is that adding Features
3485 // here may end up eventually getting added to a Target you didn't anticipate and have adverse consequences.
3486 //
3487 // With all that in mind, here are some guidelines we think will make long-term code maintenance
3488 // less painful for you:
3489 //
3490 // - Override this method *only* for temporary debugging purposes; e.g. if you
3491 // need to add the `profile` feature to a specific Generator, but your build system doesn't easily
3492 // let you specify per-Generator target features, this is the right tool for the job.
3493 //
3494 // - If your build system makes it infeasible to customize the build Target in a reasonable way,
3495 // it may be appropriate to permanently override this method to enable specific Features for
3496 // specific Generators (e.g., enabling `strict_float` is a likely example). In that case,
3497 // we would suggest:
3498 //
3499 // - *NEVER* change the arch/bits/os of the Target.
3500 // - Only add Features; don't remove Features.
3501 // - For Features that are architecture-specific, always check the arch/bits/os
3502 // of the Target to be sure it's what you expect... e.g. if you are enabling
3503 // AVX512, only do so if compiling for an x86-64 Target. Even if your code
3504 // doesn't target any other architecture at the present time, Future You will be
3505 // happier.
3506 // - If you mutate a target conditionally based on the incoming target, try to do so
3507 // so based only on the Target's arch/bits/os, and not at the Features set on the target.
3508 // If examining Features is unavoidable (e.g. enable $FOO only if $BAR is enabled),
3509 // do so as conservatively as possible, and always validate that the rest of the Target
3510 // is sensible for what you are doing.
3511 //
3512 // Furthermore, if you override this, please don't try to directly set the `target` (etc) GeneratorParams
3513 // directly; instead, construct the new GeneratorContext you want and call the superclass
3514 // implementation of init_from_context.
3515 //
3516 // TL;DR: overrides to this method should probably never be checked in to your source control system
3517 // (rather, the override should be temporary and local, for experimentation). If you must check in
3518 // overrides to this method, be paranoid that the Target you get could be something you don't expect.
3519 //
3520 virtual void init_from_context(const Halide::GeneratorContext &context);
3521
3522 virtual void call_configure() = 0;
3523 virtual void call_generate() = 0;
3524 virtual void call_schedule() = 0;

3541 // A Generator's creation and usage must go in a certain phase to ensure correctness;
3542 // the state machine here is advanced and checked at various points to ensure
3543 // this is the case.
3544 enum Phase {
3545 // Generator has just come into being.
3546 Created,
3547
3548 // Generator has had its configure() method called. (For Generators without
3549 // a configure() method, this phase will be skipped and will advance
3550 // directly to InputsSet.)
3551 ConfigureCalled,
3552
3553 // All Input<>/Param<> fields have been set. (Applicable only in JIT mode;
3554 // in AOT mode, this can be skipped, going Created->GenerateCalled directly.)
3555 InputsSet,
3556
3557 // Generator has had its generate() method called.
3558 GenerateCalled,
3559
3560 // Generator has had its schedule() method (if any) called.
3561 ScheduleCalled,
3562 } phase{Created};

3592 * this ExternalCode appended to the Module that is finally
3593 * compiled using the Generator. This allows encapsulating
3594 * functionality that depends on external libraries or handwritten

3597 * code block is not duplicated in the output. Halide does not do
3598 * anything other than to compare names for equality. To guarantee
3599 * uniqueness in public code, we suggest using a Java style
3600 * inverted domain name followed by organization specific
3601 * naming. E.g.:
3602 * com.yoyodyne.overthruster.0719acd19b66df2a9d8d628a8fefba911a0ab2b7
3603 *
3604 * See test/generator/external_code_generator.cpp for example use. */

3610 * be removed in Halide 16. You may continue to use them in Halide 15
3611 * by defining HALIDE_ALLOW_GENERATOR_EXTERNAL_CODE when building Halide. */

3683 // Allow Buffer<> if:
3684 // -- we are assigning it to an Input<Buffer<>> (with compatible type and dimensions),
3685 // causing the Input<Buffer<>> to become a precompiled buffer in the generated code.
3686 // -- we are assigningit to an Input<Func>, in which case we just Func-wrap the Buffer<>.
3687 template<typename T, int Dims>
3688 std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const Buffer<T, Dims> &arg) {
3689 auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3690 check_input_is_singular(in);
3691 const auto k = in->kind();
3692 if (k == Internal::ArgInfoKind::Buffer) {
3693 Halide::Buffer<> b = arg;
3694 StubInputBuffer<> sib(b);
3695 StubInput si(sib);
3696 return {si};
3697 } else if (k == Internal::ArgInfoKind::Function) {
3698 Halide::Func f(arg.name() + "_im");
3699 f(Halide::_) = arg(Halide::_);
3700 StubInput si(f);
3701 return {si};
3702 } else {
3703 check_input_kind(in, Internal::ArgInfoKind::Buffer); // just to trigger assertion
3704 return {};
3705 }
3706 }
3707
3708 // Allow Input<Buffer<>> if:
3709 // -- we are assigning it to another Input<Buffer<>> (with compatible type and dimensions),
3710 // allowing us to simply pipe a parameter from an enclosing Generator to the Invoker.
3711 // -- we are assigningit to an Input<Func>, in which case we just Func-wrap the Input<Buffer<>>.
3712 template<typename T, int Dims>
3713 std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const GeneratorInput<Buffer<T, Dims>> &arg) {
3714 auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3715 check_input_is_singular(in);
3716 const auto k = in->kind();
3717 if (k == Internal::ArgInfoKind::Buffer) {
3718 StubInputBuffer<> sib = arg;
3719 StubInput si(sib);
3720 return {si};
3721 } else if (k == Internal::ArgInfoKind::Function) {
3722 Halide::Func f = arg.funcs().at(0);
3723 StubInput si(f);
3724 return {si};
3725 } else {
3726 check_input_kind(in, Internal::ArgInfoKind::Buffer); // just to trigger assertion
3727 return {};
3728 }
3729 }
3730
3731 // Allow Func iff we are assigning it to an Input<Func> (with compatible type and dimensions).
3732 std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const Func &arg) {
3733 auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3734 check_input_kind(in, Internal::ArgInfoKind::Function);
3735 check_input_is_singular(in);
3736 const Halide::Func &f = arg;
3737 StubInput si(f);
3738 return {si};
3739 }
3740
3741 // Allow vector<Func> iff we are assigning it to an Input<Func[]> (with compatible type and dimensions).
3742 std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const std::vector<Func> &arg) {
3743 auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3744 check_input_kind(in, Internal::ArgInfoKind::Function);
3745 check_input_is_array(in);
3746 // My kingdom for a list comprehension...
3747 std::vector<StubInput> siv;
3748 siv.reserve(arg.size());
3749 for (const auto &f : arg) {
3750 siv.emplace_back(f);
3751 }
3752 return siv;
3753 }
3754
3755 // Expr must be Input<Scalar>.
3756 std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const Expr &arg) {
3757 auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3758 check_input_kind(in, Internal::ArgInfoKind::Scalar);
3759 check_input_is_singular(in);
3760 StubInput si(arg);
3761 return {si};
3762 }
3763
3764 // (Array form)
3765 std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const std::vector<Expr> &arg) {
3766 auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3767 check_input_kind(in, Internal::ArgInfoKind::Scalar);
3768 check_input_is_array(in);
3769 std::vector<StubInput> siv;
3770 siv.reserve(arg.size());
3771 for (const auto &value : arg) {
3772 siv.emplace_back(value);
3773 }
3774 return siv;
3775 }
3776
3777 // Any other type must be convertible to Expr and must be associated with an Input<Scalar>.
3778 // Use is_arithmetic since some Expr conversions are explicit.
3779 template<typename T,
3780 typename std::enable_if<std::is_arithmetic<T>::value>::type * = nullptr>
3781 std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const T &arg) {
3782 auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3783 check_input_kind(in, Internal::ArgInfoKind::Scalar);
3784 check_input_is_singular(in);
3785 // We must use an explicit Expr() ctor to preserve the type
3786 Expr e(arg);
3787 StubInput si(e);
3788 return {si};
3789 }
3790
3791 // (Array form)
3792 template<typename T,
3793 typename std::enable_if<std::is_arithmetic<T>::value>::type * = nullptr>
3794 std::vector<StubInput> build_input(size_t i, const std::vector<T> &arg) {
3795 auto *in = param_info().inputs().at(i);
3796 check_input_kind(in, Internal::ArgInfoKind::Scalar);
3797 check_input_is_array(in);
3798 std::vector<StubInput> siv;
3799 siv.reserve(arg.size());
3800 for (const auto &value : arg) {
3801 // We must use an explicit Expr() ctor to preserve the type;
3802 // otherwise, implicit conversions can downgrade (e.g.) float -> int
3803 Expr e(value);
3804 siv.emplace_back(e);
3805 }
3806 return siv;
3807 }

3933private:
3934 // std::is_member_function_pointer will fail if there is no member of that name,
3935 // so we use a little SFINAE to detect if there are method-shaped members.
3936 template<typename>
3937 struct type_sink { typedef void type; };
3938
3939 template<typename T2, typename = void>
3940 struct has_configure_method : std::false_type {};
3941
3942 template<typename T2>
3943 struct has_configure_method<T2, typename type_sink<decltype(std::declval<T2>().configure())>::type> : std::true_type {};
3944
3945 template<typename T2, typename = void>
3946 struct has_generate_method : std::false_type {};
3947
3948 template<typename T2>
3949 struct has_generate_method<T2, typename type_sink<decltype(std::declval<T2>().generate())>::type> : std::true_type {};
3950
3951 template<typename T2, typename = void>
3952 struct has_schedule_method : std::false_type {};
3953
3954 template<typename T2>
3955 struct has_schedule_method<T2, typename type_sink<decltype(std::declval<T2>().schedule())>::type> : std::true_type {};
3956
3957 Pipeline build_pipeline_impl() {
3958 T *t = (T *)this;
3959 // No: configure() must be called prior to this
3960 // (and in fact, prior to calling set_inputs).
3961 //
3962 // t->call_configure_impl();
3963
3964 t->call_generate_impl();
3965 t->call_schedule_impl();
3966 return get_pipeline();
3967 }
3968
3969 void call_configure_impl() {
3970 pre_configure();
3971 if constexpr (has_configure_method<T>::value) {
3972 T *t = (T *)this;
3973 static_assert(std::is_void<decltype(t->configure())>::value, "configure() must return void");
3974 t->configure();
3975 }
3976 post_configure();
3977 }
3978
3979 void call_generate_impl() {
3980 pre_generate();
3981 static_assert(has_generate_method<T>::value, "Expected a generate() method here.");
3982 T *t = (T *)this;
3983 static_assert(std::is_void<decltype(t->generate())>::value, "generate() must return void");
3984 t->generate();
3985 post_generate();
3986 }
3987
3988 void call_schedule_impl() {
3989 pre_schedule();
3990 if constexpr (has_schedule_method<T>::value) {
3991 T *t = (T *)this;
3992 static_assert(std::is_void<decltype(t->schedule())>::value, "schedule() must return void");
3993 t->schedule();
3994 }
3995 post_schedule();
3996 }
3997
3998protected:
3999 Pipeline build_pipeline() override {
4000 ensure_configure_has_been_called();
4001 return this->build_pipeline_impl();
4002 }
4003
4004 void call_configure() override {
4005 this->call_configure_impl();
4006 }
4007
4008 void call_generate() override {
4009 this->call_generate_impl();
4010 }
4011
4012 void call_schedule() override {
4013 this->call_schedule_impl();
4014 }

4183// HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR_ALIAS() can be used to create an an alias-with-a-particular-set-of-param-values
4184// for a given Generator in the build system. Normally, you wouldn't want to do this;
4185// however, some existing Halide clients have build systems that make it challenging to
4186// specify GeneratorParams inside the build system, and this allows a somewhat simpler
4187// customization route for them. It's highly recommended you don't use this for new code.
4188//
4189// The final argument is really an initializer-list of GeneratorParams, in the form
4190// of an initializer-list for map<string, string>:
4191//
4192// { { "gp-name", "gp-value"} [, { "gp2-name", "gp2-value" }] }
4193//
4194// It is specified as a variadic template argument to allow for the fact that the embedded commas
4195// would otherwise confuse the preprocessor; since (in this case) all we're going to do is
4196// pass it thru as-is, this is fine (and even MSVC's 'broken' __VA_ARGS__ should be OK here).
4197#define HALIDE_REGISTER_GENERATOR_ALIAS(GEN_REGISTRY_NAME, ORIGINAL_REGISTRY_NAME, ...) \
4198 namespace halide_register_generator { \
4199 struct halide_global_ns; \
4200 namespace ORIGINAL_REGISTRY_NAME##_ns { \
4201 std::unique_ptr<Halide::Internal::AbstractGenerator> factory(const Halide::GeneratorContext &context); \
4202 } \
